    excerpt: "Gum disease is often thought of as a purely dental problem, but research over the past two decades has revealed that it can have far-reaching effects on your overall health. The bacteria and inflammat...",
    metaDescription: "Gum disease is often thought of as a purely dental problem, but research over the past two decades has revealed that it can have far-reaching effects on...",
    readTime: "2 min read",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559757175-5700dde675bc?w=800&q=80",
    content: `<p><a href="/gum-disease-treatment/">Gum disease</a> is often thought of as a purely dental problem, but research over the past two decades has revealed that it can have far-reaching effects on your overall health. The bacteria and inflammation associated with periodontal disease do not stay confined to your mouth — they can impact your entire body. At <strong>Uplift Dental &amp; Orthodontics</strong> in <strong>Garden Grove, CA</strong>, we take gum disease seriously because we know your oral health and your general health are deeply connected.</p><h2>The Oral-Systemic Connection</h2><p>Your mouth is the gateway to your body, and the bacteria that cause gum disease can enter your bloodstream through inflamed gum tissue. Once in the bloodstream, these bacteria can travel throughout your body and contribute to inflammation in other areas. This chronic inflammation is believed to be a key link between gum disease and several serious health conditions.</p><h2>Heart Disease and Stroke</h2><p>Multiple studies have found that people with gum disease are at a higher risk for heart disease and stroke. The bacteria from infected gums can contribute to the buildup of plaque in the arteries (atherosclerosis), increasing the risk of heart attack and stroke. While gum disease is not the sole cause of heart disease, maintaining healthy gums is an important part of heart health.</p><h2>Diabetes</h2><p>The relationship between gum disease and diabetes is a two-way street. People with diabetes are more susceptible to infections, including gum disease. At the same time, gum disease can make it harder to control blood sugar levels, potentially worsening diabetes. Treating gum disease has been shown to help improve blood sugar control in diabetic patients.</p><h2>Respiratory Disease</h2><p>Bacteria from infected gums can be aspirated (breathed in) into the lungs, potentially causing or worsening respiratory conditions such as pneumonia and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). This risk is especially concerning for elderly individuals and those with compromised immune systems.</p><h2>Pregnancy Complications</h2><p>Pregnant women with gum disease may face a higher risk of premature birth and low birth weight babies. The bacteria and inflammation associated with periodontal disease are believed to interfere with fetal development. This is one reason why dental care during pregnancy is so important.</p><h2>Prevention Is Key</h2><p>The good news is that gum disease is largely preventable with good oral hygiene and regular dental care. Brush twice daily, floss daily, eat a balanced diet, avoid tobacco, and visit Uplift Dental for regular <a href="/dental-cleaning/">cleanings</a> and checkups. If you notice signs of gum disease such as bleeding gums, persistent bad breath, or receding gums, schedule an appointment right away.</p><h2>Protect Your Gums, Protect Your Health</h2><p><strong>Call Uplift Dental &amp; Orthodontics at <a href="tel:7148983308">${PRACTICE.phone.display}</a></strong> to schedule your gum health evaluation in <strong>${PRACTICE.address.city}, ${PRACTICE.address.state} ${PRACTICE.address.zip}</strong>. Your smile and your body will thank you.</p>`,
