    tags: [],
    excerpt: "When you lose a tooth, replacing it promptly is important for your oral health, your appearance, and your ability to eat and speak comfortably. Two of the most common replacement options are dental br...",
    metaDescription: "When you lose a tooth, replacing it promptly is important for your oral health, your appearance, and your ability to eat and speak comfortably.",
    readTime: "2 min read",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1606811971618-4486d14f3f99?w=800&q=80",
    content: `<p>When you lose a tooth, replacing it promptly is important for your oral health, your appearance, and your ability to eat and speak comfortably. Two of the most common replacement options are <a href="/dental-bridges/">dental bridges</a> and <a href="/dental-implants/">dental implants</a>. Both are excellent solutions, but which one is right for you depends on several factors. Here is a comprehensive comparison from <strong>Uplift Dental &amp; Orthodontics</strong> in <strong>Garden Grove, CA</strong>.</p><h2>How Dental Bridges Work</h2><p>A dental bridge literally bridges the gap created by one or more missing teeth. It consists of one or more artificial teeth (pontics) held in place by <a href="/dental-crowns/">dental crowns</a> cemented onto the adjacent natural teeth. Bridges are fixed in place and cannot be removed. They are a proven, reliable option that has been used in dentistry for decades.</p><h2>How Dental Implants Work</h2><p>A dental implant replaces the entire tooth structure, including the root. A titanium post is surgically placed into the jawbone, where it integrates with the bone over several months. A custom crown is then attached to the post. Implants are independent — they do not rely on adjacent teeth for support.</p><h2>Comparing the Two Options</h2><p>In terms of longevity, implants have a clear advantage, lasting a lifetime with proper care versus 10 to 15 years for bridges. For bone health, implants stimulate the jawbone and prevent bone loss, while bridges do not. Regarding impact on surrounding teeth, bridges require the adjacent teeth to be reduced for crown placement, while implants leave neighboring teeth untouched. In terms of cost, bridges typically have a lower upfront cost, but implants offer better long-term value. For treatment time, bridges can be completed in two to three weeks, while implants take several months due to the healing period. Both options look natural when properly crafted.</p><h2>Which Is Right for You?</h2><p>Your choice depends on the health of your adjacent teeth, the condition of your jawbone, your budget, your timeline, and your long-term goals. Our team at Uplift Dental will evaluate your specific situation and help you make the best decision.</p><h2>Get Expert Advice</h2><p><strong>Call Uplift Dental &amp; Orthodontics at <a href="tel:7148983308">${PRACTICE.phone.display}</a></strong> for a consultation in <strong>${PRACTICE.address.city}, ${PRACTICE.address.state} ${PRACTICE.address.zip}</strong>. We will help you choose the right tooth replacement option for your smile.</p>`,
