    slug: "dental-care-during-pregnancy-what-every-expecting-mom-should-know",
    title: "Dental Care During Pregnancy: What Every Expecting Mom Should Know",
    date: "December 11, 2026",
    dateISO: "2026-12-11T09:00:00",
    status: "future",
    isPublished: false,
    isScheduled: true,
    category: "Oral Hygiene",
    tags: ["dental care during pregnancy", "Garden Grove dentist", "oral health during pregnancy", "pregnancy gingivitis", "prenatal dental care"],
    excerpt: "Pregnancy is an exciting time, but it also brings changes to your body that can affect your oral health. Hormonal shifts during pregnancy can increase your risk of gum disease and other dental problem...",
    metaDescription: "Pregnancy is an exciting time, but it also brings changes to your body that can affect your oral health.",
    readTime: "2 min read",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519699047748-de8e457a634e?w=800&q=80",
    content: `<p>Pregnancy is an exciting time, but it also brings changes to your body that can affect your oral health. Hormonal shifts during pregnancy can increase your risk of gum disease and other dental problems, making dental care more important than ever. At <strong>Uplift Dental &amp; Orthodontics</strong> in <strong>Garden Grove, CA</strong>, we provide safe, gentle dental care for expecting mothers throughout every stage of pregnancy.</p><h2>How Pregnancy Affects Your Oral Health</h2><p>During pregnancy, elevated levels of estrogen and progesterone can cause your gums to react more intensely to plaque, leading to a condition called pregnancy gingivitis. Symptoms include red, swollen, and tender gums that bleed easily during brushing and flossing. If left untreated, pregnancy gingivitis can progress to more serious gum disease. Morning sickness can also affect your teeth. Frequent vomiting exposes your teeth to stomach acids that can erode tooth enamel over time. Pregnancy cravings for sugary foods can increase your risk of cavities as well.</p><h2>Is Dental Care During Pregnancy Safe?</h2><p>Yes, dental care during pregnancy is not only safe but highly recommended. The <a href="https://www.ada.org/resources/research/science-and-research-institute/oral-health-topics/pregnancy" target="_blank" rel="noopener">American Dental Association</a>, the American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, and the American Academy of Pediatric Dentistry all encourage women to maintain their dental health during pregnancy. Routine checkups, <a href="/dental-cleaning/">professional cleanings</a>, and necessary dental treatments can be safely performed during pregnancy, with the second trimester being the ideal time for elective procedures.</p><h2>Essential Dental Care Tips During Pregnancy</h2><p>Continue brushing twice daily and flossing once daily. If morning sickness makes brushing difficult, rinse your mouth with a teaspoon of baking soda mixed in water to neutralize stomach acids. Eat a balanced diet rich in calcium, protein, and vitamins A, C, and D to support your baby's developing teeth. Limit sugary snacks. Do not skip your dental checkups — schedule a cleaning and exam during your second trimester. Tell your dentist that you are pregnant so we can adjust treatment accordingly.</p><h2>Schedule Your Prenatal Dental Visit</h2><p>Taking care of your smile during pregnancy is one of the best things you can do for yourself and your baby. <strong>Call Uplift Dental &amp; Orthodontics at <a href="tel:7148983308">${PRACTICE.phone.display}</a></strong> to schedule your prenatal dental appointment in <strong>${PRACTICE.address.city}, ${PRACTICE.address.state} ${PRACTICE.address.zip}</strong>.</p>`,
